{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478799","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478799"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:16:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:16:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18811"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18811","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18811"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.8,0.02,0.13,0.01,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11544"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79416"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11544","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11544"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18811"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64738"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1940"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2545"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27167"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38192"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79416","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79416"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic at 12 weeks gestation for routine antenatal care. She has no significant medical history and takes only pregnancy multivitamin supplements. She works as a veterinary nurse and has three cats at home. She reports mild fatigue but is otherwise well.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. She has several non-tender, mobile cervical lymph nodes measuring up to 2 cm. The remainder of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerology reveals positive Toxoplasma IgM and negative IgG antibodies.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute toxoplasmosis","Cytomegalovirus infection","Cat scratch disease","Infectious mononucleosis","Reactive lymphadenopathy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute toxoplasmosis\u003C/strong\u003E. The key diagnostic features include positive IgM and negative IgG antibodies to \u003Cem\u003EToxoplasma gondii\u003C/em\u003E, indicating recent primary infection. The presence of cervical lymphadenopathy and fatigue are typical symptoms, though many infections are asymptomatic. Her occupation as a veterinary nurse and cat ownership are significant risk factors, as cats are the definitive hosts for \u003Cem\u003ET. gondii\u003C/em\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECytomegalovirus infection\u003C/strong\u003E can present similarly with lymphadenopathy and fatigue, but would show positive CMV serology rather than toxoplasma antibodies. While it can also cause congenital infection, the serological pattern here is specific for toxoplasmosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECat scratch disease\u003C/strong\u003E, caused by \u003Cem\u003EBartonella henselae\u003C/em\u003E, typically presents with a primary inoculation site and painful regional lymphadenopathy. While this patient has cat exposure, the lymph nodes are non-tender and the serology is diagnostic of toxoplasmosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInfectious mononucleosis\u003C/strong\u003E caused by Epstein-Barr virus typically presents with more prominent systemic symptoms including sore throat, fever, and significant fatigue. The serological pattern would be different, showing positive EBV-specific antibodies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReactive lymphadenopathy\u003C/strong\u003E is a non-specific finding that can occur in many conditions. However, the combination of specific risk factors and positive toxoplasma serology makes this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERecognition of acute toxoplasmosis in pregnancy is crucial as it requires prompt treatment with spiramycin to reduce the risk of congenital infection. The risk of fetal transmission increases with gestational age, ranging from about 15% in the first trimester to over 70% in the third trimester.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Congenital toxoplasmosis can present with the classic triad of chorioretinitis, intracranial calcifications, and hydrocephalus.","Primary infection with Toxoplasma gondii during pregnancy requires prompt treatment to prevent fetal transmission.","Maternal toxoplasmosis is often asymptomatic but can present with lymphadenopathy and flu-like symptoms.","The combination of positive IgM and negative IgG antibodies indicates acute primary toxoplasmosis infection."],"references":["Kota AS, Shabbir N. Congenital Toxoplasmosis. [Updated 2023 Jun 26]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK545228/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64738"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18811"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64738","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64738"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-14T12:26:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-14T12:26:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"ty